Mike Clark wrote:

&gt; 
&gt; On Nov 20, 2003, at 2:19 PM, J. B. Rainsberger wrote:
&gt; 
&gt;  &gt; This is what I mean by a parameterized test case. The feature
&gt;  &gt; &quot;calculate
&gt;  &gt; a person&#39;s age by a given date.&quot; Each test is a single assertion, but
&gt;  &gt; since only the data changes, this test is data-driven, rather than
&gt;  &gt; duplicating the invocation of &quot;getAgeAsOf()&quot; in five tests.
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; -------------------
&gt;  &gt; package ca.bluejays.scouting.amateur.model.test;
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; import java.util.Date;
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; import junit.framework.*;
&gt;  &gt; import XXX.BiographicalReport;
&gt;  &gt; import XXX.PlayerFactory;
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; import com.diasparsoftware.java.util.DateUtil;
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; public class CalculateAgeTest extends TestCase {
&gt;  &gt;      private int expectedAge;
&gt;  &gt;      private Date futureDate;
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt;      public CalculateAgeTest(String testName, int expectedAge,
&gt;  &gt;              Date futureDate) {
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt;          super(testName);
&gt;  &gt;          this.expectedAge = expectedAge;
&gt;  &gt;          this.futureDate = futureDate;
&gt;  &gt;      }
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt;      public static Test suite() {
&gt;  &gt;          TestSuite suite = new TestSuite(&quot;Calculate Age&quot;);
&gt;  &gt;          suite.addTest(new CalculateAgeTest(&quot;birthday&quot;, 30, DateUtil
&gt;  &gt;                  .makeDate(2004, 5, 4)));
&gt;  &gt;          suite.addTest(new CalculateAgeTest(&quot;day before birthday&quot;, 29,
&gt;  &gt;                  DateUtil.makeDate(2004, 5, 3)));
&gt;  &gt;          suite.addTest(new CalculateAgeTest(&quot;day after birthday&quot;, 30,
&gt;  &gt;                  DateUtil.makeDate(2004, 5, 5)));
&gt;  &gt;          suite.addTest(
&gt;  &gt;                  new CalculateAgeTest(&quot;date of birth&quot;, 0, DateUtil
&gt;  &gt;                          .makeDate(1974, 5, 4)));
&gt;  &gt;          suite.addTest(
&gt;  &gt;                  new CalculateAgeTest(&quot;invalid future date&quot;, 0,
&gt;  &gt; DateUtil
&gt;  &gt;                          .makeDate(1974, 5, 3)));
&gt;  &gt;          return suite;
&gt;  &gt;      }
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt;      protected void runTest() throws Exception {
&gt;  &gt;          BiographicalReport biographicalReport = PlayerFactory
&gt;  &gt;                  .makeBiographicalReport(&quot;Joe&quot;, &quot;Rainsberger&quot;, DateUtil
&gt;  &gt;                          .makeDate(1974, 5, 4));
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt;          assertEquals(new Integer(expectedAge), biographicalReport
&gt;  &gt;                  .getAgeAsOf(futureDate));
&gt;  &gt;      }
&gt;  &gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; Could you explain what overriding runTest() buys you over using
&gt; something obvious like:
&gt; 
&gt;      public void testCalculateAge() {
&gt;           assertEquals(new Integer(expectedAge),
&gt;               biographicalReport.getAgeAsOf(futureDate));
&gt;      }
&gt; 
&gt; where biographicalReport is an instance variable initialized in
&gt; setUp().  As each run of the test method will be data-driven as
&gt; intended, it would appear to do the same thing.

I override run test because I don&#39;t want JUnit to force me to set the 
test name to the name of the test method I want to invoke. There&#39;s only 
one test, so why use reflection to get it?

&gt; I&#39;m guessing it has something to do with not wanting to create a
&gt; BiographicalReport instance on every test method.  

Well, you can&#39;t avoid that anyway. Each invocation of runTest() occurs 
in its own instance of TestCase.

 &gt; At any rate, it
&gt; seems to be reaching fairly deep in the trick bag and I&#39;m wondering
&gt; what I&#39;m missing with the obvious approach.

I avoid this constructor:

       public CalculateAgeTest(String testName, int expectedAge,
               Date futureDate) {

           super(&quot;testCalculateAge&quot;);   &lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;
           this.expectedAge = expectedAge;
           this.futureDate = futureDate;
       }

Also with the &quot;obvious&quot; approach, I can&#39;t tell one test from another: 
all the test names look the same. Which one failed?

By making the test name different from the test method name, I can use 
the test name to report specifically which line of data led to a failing 
test.
